{"title":"Multimodal Probabilistic Model-Based Planning for Human-Robot Interaction","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"In fast, interactive tasks like traffic weaving, a robot must anticipate human responses that are inherently uncertain and multimodal, and that depend both on the interaction history and on the robot’s planned future actions.","method":"Learn a sequence-to-sequence generative model p(y|x) of human future actions conditioned on joint interaction history and candidate robot future using a Conditional Variational Autoencoder. The model uses a discrete, factorized categorical latent variable z to represent high-level behavior modes, and an LSTM autoregressive decoder with a Gaussian Mixture Model output layer to capture within-mode variability and time-step-level multimodality. Training maximizes an ELBO with an inference network q(z|x,y) and employs scheduled sampling to mitigate error compounding. This structure yields interpretable modes and improved validation negative log-likelihood while explicitly modeling responses to candidate robot actions."},{"problem":"Constructing real-time robot policies under multimodal human uncertainty requires efficiently evaluating how different robot action sequences affect likely human responses, while covering disparate interaction modes.","method":"Discretize the robot’s short-horizon action space into 5 windows with 8 choices each (4096 candidate sequences) and evaluate expected cost via massive parallel sampling of human responses from the learned model. Use a two-stage pipeline: sample 16 human futures per sequence to rank candidates, then rescore the top 32 with 1024 samples each, and select the minimum-expected-cost sequence. The cost combines collision avoidance, control effort, lane-change urgency, and longitudinal disambiguation, and actions are executed in an MPC loop with 0.3 s replanning. This GPU-based procedure simulates nearly 100,000 human futures in about 0.25 s, enabling coverage of multimodal outcomes in real time."}]}
